===Notable players===
<!--Please only include inductees into the International Rugby Hall of Fame-->:''See also [[:Category:Welsh rugby union footballers]]''
[[Image:Gwyn Nichols.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[International Rugby Hall of Fame]] inductee [[Gwyn Nicholls]] who played 24 Tests for Wales between 1896 and 1906.]]
Ten former Welsh internationals have been inducted into the [[International Rugby Hall of Fame]]. <!-- Removed wikilinked names from here to avoid overlinking. Reinstate if this bothers you. -->

Known as the ''Prince of three-quarters'', [[Gwyn Nicholls]] played 24 Tests for Wales at {{rugbycentre}} between 1896 and 1906.<ref name="Nicholls1">{{cite web |url=http://www.blackandambers.co.uk/Personnel.aspx?pr=104202 |title=Gwyn Nicholls |publisher=blackandambers.co.uk |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref> He was the only Welsh player in the British Isles team of 1899, and was the star for Wales during their first golden era. Not only did he captain Wales to three Triple Crowns, but also led them to their famous victory over the All Blacks in 1905.<ref name="NicollsIRHF">{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyhalloffame.com/pages/nicholls2005.htm |title=Gwyn Nicholls |publisher=rugbyhalloffame.com |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref> On [[26 December]] [[1949]], gates bearing his name at Cardiff Arms Park were officially opened.<ref name="NicollsGates">{{cite web |url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-NICH-GWY-1875.html |title=NICHOLLS, ERITH GWYN |publisher=Welsh Biography Online |accessdate=2007-08-20 |last=Williams |first=Moelwyn }}</ref>

Named the greatest Welsh player of the 1950s by the WRU, [[Cliff Morgan]] played 25 Tests for Wales, and four for the British Lions between 1951 and 1955.<ref name="MorganHon">{{cite web |url=http://www.wru.co.uk/114_9244.php |title=Morgan honoured |publisher=wru.co.uk |date=[[2006-11-25]] |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref> Morgan played at {{fly-half}} and was one of the sport's biggest crowd-pullers during his career.<ref name="MorganIRHF">{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyhalloffame.com/pages/morgan1997.htm |title=Cliff Morgan |publisher=rugbyhalloffame.com |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref> He played during Wales Five Nations Grand Slam of 1952, and Wales' victory over the All Blacks in 1953, but he is most famous for captaining the British Lions in South Africa in 1955.<ref name="MorganLions">{{cite web |url=http://www.lionsrugby.com/pp_cliff_morgan.html |title=Cliff Morgan |publisher=lionsrugby.com |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref> One of Morgan's great friends was Carwyn James.<ref name="MorganJames">{{cite news |url=http://cis.jhu.edu/~tilak/rugby/carwyn.html |title=Lonely prince of coaches |accessdate=2007-08-20 |date=[[2001-03-22]] |publisher=The Guardian |last=Foot |first=David }}</ref> Although most notable for his coaching record, James appeared for Wales in two Tests in 1958. He coached the British Lions to their first and only series victory over New Zealand in 1971, with a team including many Welsh players.<ref name="JamesIRHF">{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyhalloffame.com/pages/james1999.htm |title=Carwyn James |publisher=rugbyhalloffame.com |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref> He also coached Welsh club Llanelli, and the [[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]] side that defeated the All Blacks in 1973. Despite this, he never coached Wales.<ref name="Barbarians">{{cite news |url=http://sport.independent.co.uk/rugby_union/article22938.ece |title=Why has rugby shortchanged the Barbarian legends of '73? |accessdate=2007-08-20 |date=[[2004-12-03]] |publisher=The Independent |last=Hewett |first=Chris }}</ref>

When Wales faced Australia on [[3 December]] [[1966]], two future Rugby Hall of Fame members made their Test debuts; [[Gerald Davies]] and [[Barry John]]. Davies played 46 Tests for Wales between 1966 and 1978. Although he started out playing in the centre, he was moved to the {{wing}} during Wales' 1969 tour of New Zealand and Australia,<ref name="DaviesBBC">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/celtic/2616131.stm |title=Gerald Davies CBE |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-08-20 |date=[[2002-12-31]] }}</ref> and eventually scored 20 Test tries for Wales. Davies also played for the Lions during their 1968 tour of South Africa and 1971 tour of New Zealand.<ref name="GDaviesIRHF">{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyhalloffame.com/pages/davies1999.htm |title=Gerald Davies |publisher=rugbyhalloffame.com |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref> Although Barry John first played for Wales in 1966, he did not secure his spot in the team until 1968.<ref name="JohnHeroes">{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/rugby-heroes/displayhero.asp?HeroID=805 |publisher=sporting-heroes.net |title=Barry John |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref> Playing at fly-half, John helped Wales to a Five Nations Grand Slam in 1971, and then the Lions to their one and only series win over the All Blacks that same year. He picked up the nickname ''The King'' in New Zealand, and in 1972 quit the sport due to the pressure his fame was causing.<ref name="JohnIRHF">{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyhalloffame.com/pages/john1997.htm |title=Barry John |publisher=rugbyhalloffame.com |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref>

Widely regarded as the greatest rugby union player of all time, [[Gareth Edwards]] played 53 Tests for Wales at {{scrum-half}} between 1967 and 1978.<ref name="EdwardsSH">{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/rugby-heroes/displayhero.asp?HeroID=1164 |publisher=sporting-heroes.net |title=Gareth Edwards |accessdate=2007-11-03 }}</ref><ref name="GEdwardsBBC">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/walesonair/database/garethedwards.shtml |title=Wales on Air - Gareth Edwards |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-11-03 }}</ref> Edwards was never dropped from the team and played all 53 of his Tests consecutively. He also played in three Lions tours; including the series victories in New Zealand in 1971, and the unbeaten tour of South Africa in 1974.<ref name="EdwardsTimes">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/columnists/paul_kimmage/article1564157.ece |title=Leader of the backs |publisher=timesonline.co.uk |date=[[2007-03-25]] |last=Kimmage |first=Paul |accessdate=2007-08-21 }}</ref> Edwards won five Triple Crowns with Wales and three Five Nations Grand Slams. He also scored a try for the Barbarians against the All Blacks in 1973, remembered as ''that try'' and considered the greatest ever try.<ref name="GEdwardsBBC"/> In 2003, Edwards was voted the greatest player of all time by ''[[Rugby World]]'' magazine.<ref name="GreatestEver">{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/SPORT/12/30/honors.edwards/index.html |title=Rugby legend Edwards handed honor |date=[[2006-12-30]] |title= Rugby legend Edwards handed honor |accessdate=2007-11-03 |publisher=cnn.com }}</ref><ref name="ThatTry">{{cite web |accessdate=2007-08-21 |title=Gareth Edwards |url=http://www.scrum.com/1200_1205.php?player=25930&includeref=dynamic |publisher=scrum.com }}</ref>

In 1969, three Hall of Fame members debuted for Wales; [[Phil Bennett]], [[Thomas Mervyn Davies|Mervyn Davies]], and [[J. P. R. Williams|JPR Williams]]. Bennett played 29 Tests for Wales. He started out playing at {{fullback}}, but after Barry John retired, he was moved to fly-half. As well as representing Wales, he played eight Tests for the Lions and captained them on their 1977 tour of New Zealand.<ref name="BennettIRHF">{{cite web |url=http://rugbyhalloffame.com/pages/bennett2005.htm |title=Phil Bennett |publisher=rugbyhalloffame.com |accessdate=2007-08-22 }}</ref> Mervyn Davies was known as ''Merve the Swerve'' and played 38 consecutive Tests for Wales between 1969 and 1976, losing only eight of them.<ref name="MDaviesIRHF">{{cite web |url=http://rugbyhalloffame.com/pages/davies2001.htm |title=Mervyn Davies |publisher=rugbyhalloffame.com |accessdate=2007-08-22 }}</ref> After captaining Wales in his last nine appearances, Davies was forced to retire due to a [[brain haemorrhage]].<ref name="MDaviesSwansea">{{cite web |url=http://www.swansearfc.co.uk/whites_gallery_browser_view.php?image_id=532 |title=Davies, Mervyn |publisher=swansearfc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-08-22 }}</ref> JPR Williams played 55 Tests for Wales between 1969 and 1981. Whilst doing so, he won six Triple Crowns, three Five Nations Grand Slams, and captained Wales for five Tests in 1979.<ref name="JPR100">{{cite web |url=http://www.100welshheroes.com/en/biography/jprwilliams |title=JPR Williams |publisher=100welshheroes.com |accessdate=2007-08-22 }}</ref> Playing at full-back, he also toured with the Lions in 1971 and 1974, before retiring temporarily in 1980. He made a brief comeback, however, in 1981, when he played his final match, against Scotland.<ref name="JPRSportingHeroes">{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/rugby-heroes/displayhero.asp?HeroID=1782 |title=J.P.R. WILLIAMS |publisher=sporting-heroes.net |accessdate=2007-08-22 }}</ref>

[[Ieuan Evans]] played for Wales between 1987 and 1998, and in the process earned 72 Welsh caps whilst Wales was transcending the amateur and professional eras. Playing mainly on the wing, Evans scored 33 tries for Wales, a record until surpassed by Gareth Thomas in 2004.<ref name="GThomasBio">{{cite web |title=Gareth Thomas, Welsh centurion |url=http://www.wru.co.uk/1391_15094.php |publisher=wru.co.uk |accessdate=2007-11-03 |date=[[2007-09-26]] }}</ref> As well as that, he was awarded seven Lions caps from the 1989, 1993 and 1997 tours.<ref name="IRHFIeuanEvans">{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyhalloffame.com/pages/evans2007.htm |title=Ieuan Evans |publisher=rugbyhalloffame.com |accessdate=2007-11-03 }}</ref><ref name="IeuanEvansBBC">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/southwest/halloffame/sport/ieuanevans.shtml |title=Ieuan Evans |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-11-03 }}</ref>

===Individual records===
[[Image:Colin Charvis.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Welsh forward [[Colin Charvis]] who has scored more tries than any other forward for Wales.]] 
Former {{fly-half}} [[Neil Jenkins]] was the first rugby player to surpass 1000 Test points, and holds the [[List of leading Rugby union Test point scorers|world record]] of 1049 points. He also holds the world record for most penalties with 248, and Welsh record for most points in a single Test match with 30.<ref name="IntRecords">{{cite news |publisher=superrugby.co.za |url=http://www.superrugby.co.za/default.asp?Id=1013&des=content&cl=yes&Scat=SUPERRUGBY/INTERNATIONALRUGBY |title=International Individual Records |accessdate=2007-08-14 |date=[[2007-08-13]] }}</ref><ref name="NeilJenkins">{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/rugby-heroes/displayhero.asp?HeroID=1719 |title=Neil Jenkins |publisher=sporting-heroes.net |accessdate=2007-08-14 }}</ref> Wales' Test try record of 40 tries is held by [[Gareth Thomas (rugby player)|Gareth Thomas]], who is also the most capped player with 100 Test caps.<ref name="GThomasBio"/><ref>This excludes three for the [[British and Irish Lions]].</ref> The record for Welsh tries by a forward is held by [[Colin Charvis]] with 20. Charvis is also Wales' most-capped forward, having played in 93 Tests, but the record for most consecutive appearances is held by [[Gareth Edwards]] who played all 53 of his Tests for Wales consecutively between 1967 and 1978.<ref name="IntRecords"/>

==Coaches==
Following the unsuccessful tour to South Africa in 1964, the WRU set up a working party on coaching. The party recommended that Welsh clubs accept the principle of coaching. David Nash was appointed as the national team's first coach in 1967, but for the 1968 tour of Argentina, the WRU initially planned not to have a coach tour with the team. Following pressure from the Welsh clubs at the WRU's [[annual general meeting]], the decision was reversed and [[Clive Rowlands]] was appointed as coach for the tour. The appointing of a coach for the team coincided with Wales' success in the Five Nations during the 1970s.<ref name="DevelopmentofCoaching"/>

List of head coaches:<ref name="CoachList">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/welsh/4858748.stm |title=Wales' former rugby coaches |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-08-22 }}</ref>
